"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_np_s10_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"4700a1",
"children":[
"Phosphate is primarily excreted through the kidneys and is reabsorbed mainly in the proximal tubule. The primary hormonal factors regulating phosphorus balance are ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"parathyroid hormone",
"children":[
"PTH"
]
},
" (which decreases phosphorus reabsorption and promotes kidney phosphate excretion) and calcitriol (which stimulates phosphate absorption in the gut). Characteristic findings in severe hypophosphatemia are ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"heart failure",
"children":[
"HF"
]
},
","
]
},
" muscle weakness, rhabdomyolysis, hemolytic anemia, and metabolic encephalopathy."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d38a8d",
"children":[
"Common causes include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0ec887",
"children":[
"refeeding after starvation"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0d4912",
"children":[
"insulin administration for severe hyperglycemia"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c41db4",
"children":[
"hungry bone syndrome following parathyroidectomy"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"2640be",
"children":[
"respiratory alkalosis"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"6d7056",
"children":[
"chronic diarrhea"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d372cf",
"children":[
"chronic alcoholism"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"dc3991",
"children":[
"hyperparathyroidism"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a21823",
"children":[
"vitamin D deficiency"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"17cddb",
"children":[
"If the cause of hypophosphatemia is not evident from the history, a 24-hour urine phosphate collection or calculation of the ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"fractional excretion of filtered phosphate",
"children":[
"FE",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"small",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"PO"
]
},
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
}
]
},
" from a random urine sample can help differentiate renal from extrarenal causes. The FE",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"small",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"PO"
]
},
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" can be calculated as follows:"
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a122a5",
"children":[
"(Urine PO",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" × Serum Creatinine × 100)/(Serum PO",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" × Urine Creatinine)"
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b3229b",
"children":[
"Urine phosphate excretion >100 mg/d or an FE",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"small",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"PO"
]
},
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" >5% indicates renal phosphate wasting."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_np_s10_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"67a8b1",
"children":[
"In asymptomatic patients, administer oral phosphorus replacement as a sodium or potassium salt. Parenteral therapy with either of these agents is indicated for symptomatic patients or for those whose phosphorus level is <2 mg/dL."
]
}
]
}
]
